name: N,N-diethyl-2-[2-(2-methylphenyl)-2-oxoethyl]benzamide
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-2483
Reason:
To predict the melting point for N,N-diethyl-2-[2-(2-methylphenyl)-2-oxoethyl]benzamide, we first consider the basic unit benzene which typically has a melting point around 5.5°C. Each structural feature or functional group in the molecule will adjust this base value either up or down. Here are the contributions of the different functional groups in the molecule: 
- Benzamide group: +130°C (Amide groups generally raise the melting point due to hydrogen bonding capabilities and the resonance stabilization.) 
- Methyl groups directly attached to the benzene ring: +5°C each (due to increased hydrophobicity and van der Waals forces, albeit a small effect because of their size.) 
- Additional benzene ring: +20°C (Each aromatic ring typically increases rigidity and symmetry, which generally raises the melting point.) 
- Ethyl groups on the nitrogen: -40°C each (Alkyl groups can decrease the melting point due to decreased symmetry and potential disruptions to crystal lattice formation.) 
- Ketone (as part of the 2-oxoethyl group): +10°C (Ketone groups can form dipoles increasing intermolecular forces, but the effect is somewhat moderated by the molecular size and structure.) 
Taking all these into consideration, the estimated melting point shift would be calculated as follows: 
5.5 (base benzene) + 130 (benzamide) + 10 (methyl groups) + 20 (additional benzene ring) - 80 (ethyl groups) + 10 (ketone) = 95.5°C adjustment from the base value of benzene. Hence, the predicted melting point is 5.5 + 95.5 = 101°C.
